observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the MAcco:
Prepare the necessary journal entries to adjust the remaining reconciling items/discrepancies totaling ₱159,997.31 noted herein to accurately present the MLGU’s actual cash position for each period and submit to the Audit Team a copy of the JEV of the already adjusted ₱276,816.40 for further evaluation;
Prepare year-end adjusting entries to revert the unreleased checks totaling ₱43,350.00 to the CIB account and recognize the corresponding liability/payable account;
Provide written explanation on the noted significant variance in the recorded book balance of the CIB-LCCA in the 20% DF and the ending balances in the SCBAA (as well as on the 5% DRRMF), and furnish proofs of reconciliations undertaken together with the MT and MBO; and
Cause the timely preparation and submission of BRSs including the original copies of debit/credit memos.
We also recommended the MT to maintain her cashbook and update and accomplish the certification of transactions at the end of each month as required by the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, and thereafter, reconcile his cash book records with the accounting ledgers.

We recommended the following:
The MAcco to draw the necessary adjusting journal entries to reclassify the procured premium rice for stockpiling amounting to ₱42,500.00 to the proper inventory account, Welfare Goods for Distribution;
The GSO and/or Inventory Committee to regularly submit the inventory count to be undertaken semestrally, as of June 30 and December 31, and to prepare RPCI and submit the same to the Office of Auditor every July 31 and January 31 each year;
The MAcco and the GSO to prepare and maintain SLCs and Stock Cards (SC) to account the issuance of its inventories and conduct periodic reconciliation between records, and if with discrepancy, shall be verified and/or adjusted accordingly;
The MDRRMO and MSWDO to regularly submit the inventory of goods and the duly received distribution lists to the GSO upon released of the relief goods;
The GSO to consolidate weekly the RIS using the SSMI and submit the same to the MAcco for the computation of the cost of the relief goods issued and draw JEV to recognized expense in the period in which they relate; and
The MAcco to disclose in the Notes to FS the amount of inventories recognized as expense during the audit period.

We recommended the following:
The Management to clarify with the BIR the rule on taxability of cooperatives with respect to their transactions to non-members specifically on withholding of both income tax and VAT;
The MAcco:
 to resolve the above-mentioned reconciling items and identify the cause of discrepancies in the SLs to come up with a more accurate and reliable information;
 to always require the attachment of COTE on all payments made to cooperatives and after the clarification with BIR to withhold taxes on income payment to cooperatives if applicable. Further, require the cooperatives to furnish copies of their CDA registration and COTE; and
The MT to remit on time all withheld taxes to the BIR.

We recommended the following:
The MAcco to cause the timely preparation and submission of BRSs as required by COA Circular No. 96-011;
The MT to duly prepare the RCI and RCD with all its supporting documents and submit the same to the Municipal Accounting Office;
The MAcco to prepare the necessary journal entries to adjust all reconciling items/discrepancies noted herein. Moreover, we recommended the regular adjustment of reconciling items identified to accurately present the LGU’s actual cash position for each period;
The MT to regularly accomplish the certification of transactions at the end of each month as required by the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, and thereafter, reconcile her cash book records with the accounting ledgers;
The MAcco together with the MT and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile their records and the above-noted variances in the 20% DF and 5% DRRMF appearing in the FS and SCBAA, and thereafter, undertake the same regularly; and
Cash accounts to be monitored by key heads of offices consistently and should be presented fairly in accordance with IPSAS 1 and other accounting rules and regulations.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Mayor, through the concerned office, to ensure submission of MOA and supporting documents to the Office of the Auditor within five (5) working days from perfection thereof, in keeping with COA Circular No. 2009-001;
The MAcco, MT and implementing departments to coordinate and confirm whether projects charged to the above-mentioned fund transfers were actually completed and determine whether there are any other outstanding obligations chargeable to the funds;
The MAcco and MT to determine if the unutilized balances accrue to the NGAs or the LGU in instances of counterpart funds;
If upon verification the projects were completed and no outstanding obligations accrue to the funds, the LGU shall take the following actions:
For funds accruing the NGAs, immediately return the unexpended balances as at year-end to these Source Agencies (SA). If the SA cannot be identified, immediately remit the remaining idle funds to the Bureau of Treasury; and
For counterpart LGU funds, the Local Finance Committee to undertake corresponding evaluation and give recommendation on the proper disposition of funds to other priority projects.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the MAcco and Municipal Budget Officer to review the discrepancies observed in the Notes to FS as compared to the Annual Budget as of December 31, 2023 and provide the Office of the Auditor with written explanation on the inconsistencies in amounts and balances;
Require the MAcco to make the necessary adjusting entries relative to the misclassified/misstated accounts;
Instruct the MDRRMO, together with the ME and in cooperation with the heads of other offices concerned, to expedite and ensure the full implementation of all identified priority PPAs to optimize the utilization of the 5% LDRRMF;
Direct the LDRRM Officer and the MDRRM Council to monitor the implementation of the LDRRM PPAs to ensure that the public receive the benefits that may accrue from the utilization of the fund within the targeted timelines; and
Strictly and prudently comply with all the rules and regulations laid out relative to LDRRM Fund.

We recommended the following:
The Municipal Development Council to see to it that their resolved PPAs for implementation be consistent with the fund source in the approved Annual Investment Plan (AIP);
The Sanggunian Bayan to properly review the resolution submitted by the MDC for inclusion in the Local Expenditure Program (LEP) before its enactment to ensure that PPAs are sourced in their appropriate fund consistent with the approved Annual Investment Plan;
The MPD Officer to always be consistent and accurate with the PPAs indicated in the AIP as to fund source and other relevant details;
The Municipal Budget Officer to inform the implementing departments of their status of obligations for the latter to be prompted of any PPAs which are stagnant and non-moving to implement an efficient and effective strategy so that the 20% DF is optimally utilized; and
Management, as a whole, to fast track the implementation of the Project “Improvement/Upgrading of Poblacion Water System” covering 5 Barangays especially that almost one-fourth of the allocation is given to this project as well as other PPAs programed under the 20% DF. If not feasible, consider re-aligning the projects to PPAs which are easier and feasible to implement. Also, we recommended the concerned Officials and Employees to always coordinate well to put up a strategy that will result to more efficient and effective result.

We recommended the following:
The end-user or requesting office to obtain certified copies of the (1) page of the approved APP or Supplemental APP, whichever is applicable, and (2) submitted Contract or Purchase Order stamped “Received” by COA to be attached to the Disbursement Voucher;
The BAC Secretariat to submit to the Office of Auditor copies of perfected contracts or Purchase Order along with their required attachments which shall be the basis of issuing a certified copy of the submitted Contract or Purchase Order stamped “Received” by COA;
The BAC Secretariat to issue a stamped certified copy of the page of the approved APP or Supplemental APP to facilitate regularity of all procurements;
The MAcco to require from contractors Progress Billings for progress payments which may serve as a basis for recording transactions to the CIP account and to effectively execute her pre-audit functions;
The Municipal Mayor as Head of Agency to sign and issue Certificate of Acceptance to signify the acceptance and satisfaction of Management as to the completed projects in behalf of the LGU Dupax del Sur; and
Management and all concerned offices are enjoined to strictly comply to the aforesaid rules and regulations on the documentary requirements and ensure that these are complete and duly attached to the disbursement vouchers to avoid audit suspension, if warranted.

We recommended to Management the following:
the Municipal Assessor to prepare and submit to the Municipal Treasurer, on or before the thirty-first (31st) day of December each year, an assessment roll containing a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;
based from the submitted report from the Municipal Assessor, the Municipal Treasurer to update its records and thereafter forward a copy of certified list of the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year based on the Real Property Tax Account Registers to the Municipal Accountant as a basis in setting-up the Real Property Tax Receivables.

We recommended to Management the following:
The Municipal Mayor, together with the Municipal Planning and Development Council, through the Municipal Planning and Development Officer, judicially plan and evaluate the LGU’s PPAs for each budget year to properly identify priority development projects and their feasibility, to mitigate if not totally prevent delays in the implementation;
the Municipal Planning and Development Council (MPDC) include in the Annual Investment Plan (AIP) only those that can be implemented during the year through efficient planning and procurement activities;
the Municipal Engineer, in cooperation with the heads of other offices concerned, expedite and ensure the full implementation of all identified priority PPAs to optimize the utilization of the 20% development fund as mandated under DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1.

The Audit Team recommended that: 

the BAC prepare a resolution delegating to specific officials, personnel or committee or office the conduct of Direct Retail Purchase of POL. Likewise, the Municipal Mayor shall prepare and issue an issuance or an order for the purpose;

since the Municipal Mayor is the delegating authority for the direct retail purchase, each office estimate its necessary POL requirements within the fiscal year, including provisions for foreseeable emergencies based on historical records, that will be subjected to direct retail purchase and consolidate it in the Annual Procurement Plan of the Mayor’s Office in its entirety including any amendment thereto which shall be reflected in the supplemental APP;

the Municipal Mayor, being the Head of the Procuring Entity, approve all direct retail purchase of POL; and

the direct purchase must be made from retailers or dealers identified to be capable of delivering the required POL products at the most reasonable retail price.

observations.managementAction:
The MTO issue notices to realty tax delinquents. In addition to the issuance of notice, the MTO carryout the following:

House to house collection and distribution of realty tax;
Tax information and dialogue to the delinquent taxpayers.

observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:

At the close of each business day, collectors shall turn over all their collections intact to the Liquidating Officer and prepare the corresponding Report of Collections and Deposits;

The Liquidating Officer update daily the cashbook records, foot and reconcile with actual cash on hand;

Strictly monitor accountable forms issued, including those of the barangays, and remind concerned accountable officers of their responsibility to remit their collections regularly as prescribed above; and

Require accountable officers to report and remit first all accountable forms received and their collections prior the issuance of additional accountable forms.

